That&#39;s not the truth. The real reason is you&#39;re processing a **JSON payload**. The json payload must be **deserialized** into  `ICollection&lt;SkillBindDto&gt;` firstly and then the **validator** could validate it. 

When processing your payload with **an invalid `GUID`** property, the **deserialization fails too early** so there&#39;ll be **no further binding/validation** for other properties.

&gt; *Is there a way to get all model state errors on one trip?*

As I said above, the issue happens because the JSON Deserailziation fails.

If you would like using the JSON format, you tell MVC how to process the invalid property. For example, create a custom `JsonConverter` :

```
public class MyCustomConverter : JsonConverter
{
    public override object ReadJson(JsonReader reader, Type objectType, object existingValue, JsonSerializer serializer)
    {
        var dt= reader.Value;
        ... // because the processing rules depends on your business, 
        ... //     I can&#39;t write all the codes here.
        ... // e.g.
        ... //     create a null(object) or default(value) if invalid
    }
}
```


## An Easy Walkaround


As a much easier **walkaround**, you can send a **form payload instead of `application/json`**. 

A [form payload](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Methods/POST) is encoded as key-value pairs separated by &#39;&amp;&#39;, with a &#39;=&#39; between the key and the value, which looks like query string. When you submit a HTML `&lt;form /&gt;` in old days, you&#39;re actually send a form payload. 

Frist, remove the `[FromBody]` attribute in your action:

&lt;pre&gt;
[HttpPost()]
public async Task&amp;lt;ActionResult&amp;lt;IReadOnlyCollection&amp;lt;SkillDto&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&amp;gt; Create(&lt;strike&gt;[FromBody]&lt;/strike&gt;ICollection&amp;lt;SkillBindDto&amp;gt; skills, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    ...
}
&lt;/pre&gt;

And then send the payload in format of `application/x-www-form-urlencoded`. You might use [`new FormData(formElementId)`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/FormData/Using_FormData_Objects#Creating_a_FormData_object_from_scratch) to construct such a form payload. I create a helper function that maps a JSON to form-data :
```javascript
function createFormPayload(name,o){
    var payload = {};
    function _objectNotNull(value){
        return value !== null &amp;&amp; typeof value === &quot;object&quot;;
    }
    function _create(prefix,obj) {
        for(var prop in obj) {
            if (obj.hasOwnProperty(prop)) {
                var key = &quot;&quot;;
                if(prefix){
                    key = isNaN(prop)? key = prefix + &quot;.&quot; + prop : key = prefix + &quot;.[&quot; + prop + &quot;]&quot;;
                }else{
                    key = isNaN(prop)? key = prop : key = &quot;[&quot; + prop + &quot;]&quot;;
                }
                var value = obj[prop];
                if(_objectNotNull(value)) 
                    _create(key, value); 
                else 
                    payload[key]=value;
            }
        }
    };
    _create(name,o);
    return payload;
}
```

And now we can send the `skills` to form-data object:
```javascript
var skills= [
