Instead of using a Rectangle that is transformed by its `RenderTransform`, you might better use a Path with a transformed `RectangleGeometry`.

You could overlay the displayed Path with another one that has a transparent `Stroke` and `Fill` and a wide enough `StrokeThickness` to capture mouse input in the proximity of the displayed rectangle.

    &lt;Window.DataContext&gt;
        &lt;local:ViewModel/&gt;
    &lt;/Window.DataContext&gt;
    &lt;Canvas&gt;
        &lt;Path Data=&quot;{Binding TransformedRectangle}&quot;
              StrokeThickness=&quot;3&quot; Stroke=&quot;Black&quot;/&gt;

        &lt;Path Data=&quot;{Binding TransformedRectangle}&quot;
              StrokeThickness=&quot;60&quot; StrokeLineJoin=&quot;Round&quot;
              Stroke=&quot;Transparent&quot; Fill=&quot;Transparent&quot;
              MouseLeftButtonDown=&quot;PathMouseLeftButtonDown&quot;/&gt;
    &lt;/Canvas&gt;

A sample view model that provides the transformed geometry:

    public class ViewModel
    {
        public RectangleGeometry TransformedRectangle { get; } = new RectangleGeometry();

        public ViewModel()
        {
            var transform = new TransformGroup();
            transform.Children.Add(new ScaleTransform(2, 1));
            transform.Children.Add(new SkewTransform(30, 0));
            transform.Children.Add(new RotateTransform(45, 250, 150));

            TransformedRectangle.Rect = new Rect(100, 100, 100, 100);
            TransformedRectangle.Transform = transform;
        }
    }

